The cities of Tshwane and Joburg have been chasing up electricity defaulters, but Eskom is also hunting down those who don't pay in other areas. eNCA's Pule Letshwiti-Jones reports. Courtesy of #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - Eskom is identifying the worst of its non-payment offenders. Ekurhuleni has been added to that list, owing the power utility R544-million. Eskom's also planning to name and shame customers not paying their bills. WATCH: SA's Electricity Crisis | Ekurhuleni named and shamed The City of Ekurhuleni has promised R544-million to pay Eskom to settle its electricity bill. But Eskom says the city failed to honour its agreement to settle its debt. READ: SA's electricity crisis | Eskom unhappy with Nersa decision The city has told eNCA it has never defaulted and has always adhered to its payment arrangement. The power utility is nevertheless slapping it with a hefty penalty fee. Eskom says it will be knocking on the doors of other municipalities in Gauteng -- including Emfuleni and West Rand -- to pay up. Eskom is identifying the worst of its non-payment offenders. Eskom's also planning to name and shame customers not paying their bills. eNCA reporter Pule Letshwiti-Jones has that story. Courtesy of #DStv403 